e piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"FONTAINE","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Armand, Andre, Normand, Pierre, Emile, Fernand, Lucien, Marcel, Adelard, Henri, Jacques, Laurent.","French and Walloon: topographic name for someone living near a spring or well, from Old French <i>fontaine</i>, from Late Latin <i>fontana</i>, a derivative of Latin <i>fons</i> (see   Font  ); or a habitational name from Fontaine, the name of several places in various parts of France. Compare   Fountaine  .","Shortened form of French   Lafontaine  , a variant of 1 above."],"variants":[{"name":"Fontenot","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Emile, Ulysse, Andrus, Alcide, Andre, Edouard, Lucien, Marise, Monique, Remy.","French: variant of <b>Fonteneau</b> (and, in North America, an altered form of this), a topographic name from a diminutive of Old French <i>fontaine</i> ‘spring, well’ (see   Fontaine  ), or a habitational name from any of several places mainly in the westcentral part of France so named. The surname <i>Fontenot</i> is very rare in France.","History: Jean-Louis Fonteneau/Fontenot from Montierneuf in Vienne, France, married Louise-Angélique Henry in Mobile, AL, in 1726."]},{"name":"Fontenelle","meanings":["French: topographic name from a diminutive of Old French <i>fontaine</i> ‘spring, well’ (see   Fontaine  ), or a habitational name from (La) Fontenelle, the name of several places in various parts of France, of the same origin."]},{"name":"Fontenette","meanings":["French: topographic name from a diminutive of Old French <i>fontaine</i> ‘spring, well’ (see   Fontaine  ), or a habitational name from Fontenette, the name of several places mainly in the central part of France, of the same origin."]},{"name":"Fountain","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): from one or more of the places in France named Fontaine, Fonteyne, or Lafontaine (see   Fontaine  ).","English: topographic name for someone who lived near a spring or well, from Middle English <i>fontayne</i> (Old French <i>fontaine</i>) ‘spring, fountain’, sometimes with a plural <i>-s</i>, and synonymous with   Well  , of which <i>Fountain(es)</i> may sometimes have been a translation."]},{"name":"Font","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Carlos, Juan, Luis, Miguel, Rafael, Eduardo, Raul, Eugenio, Pedro, Roberto, Aida.","Catalan and southern French: topographic name for someone living near a spring or well, Catalan and Occitan <i>font</i> ‘spring, well’ (from Latin <i>fons</i>, genitive <i>fontis</i>).","English: variant of   Fant  ."]},{"name":"Fontan","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Angel, Benigno, Carlos, Jose, Juana, Manuel, Pedro, Adolfo, Aida, Alfredo, Candido, Emilia.","Spanish and Galician (<b>Fontán</b>): habitational name from any of the many places called Fontán, from <i>fontán</i> ‘spring’.","French: variant of   Fontaine  ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Mahaut DE FONTAINE was born in 1195, in Fontaine-l'Évêque, Hainaut, Belgium, her father, Wauthier IV de Fontaines, was 55 and her mother, Basilie DE CONDÉ DE TRITH, was 26. She had at least 1 son with Baudouin Ier DE HENIN LIETARD. She died in 1235, at the age of 40."},"et":{"1195–1235":"1195–1235","1185–1259":"1185–1259","1200–Male":"1200–Surnud","1140–1209":"1140–1209","1169–Female":"1169–Surnud","1259":"1259","1235":"1235","1169":"1169","Abt 1200":"umbes 1200","1200":"1200","1185":"1185","1195":"1195","1140":"1140","1209":"1209","Fontaine-l'Évêque, Hainaut, Belgique":"Fontaine-l'Évêque, Hainaut, Belgia"},"fi":{"1195–1235":"1195–1235","1185–1259":"1185–1259","1200–Male":"1200–Kuollut","1140–1209":"1140–1209","1169–Female":"1169–Kuollut","1259":"1259","1235":"1235","1169":"1169","Abt 1200":"noin 1200","1200":"1200","1185":"1185","1195":"1195","1140":"1140","1209":"1209","Fontaine